{{Infobox glacier | name = Beardmore Glacier | other_name = | photo = Beardmore Glacier - Antarctica.JPG | photo_width = | photo_alt = Aerial view of the Beardmore Glacier in 1956 | photo_caption = Aerial view of the Beardmore Glacier in 1956 | type = Valley glacier | location = [[Queen Maud Mountains]] | coordinates = {{coord|83|45|S|171|0|E|region:AQ|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | coords_ref = | map = Antarctica | map_width = | map_alt = | map_caption = Location of Beardmore Glacier in [[Antarctica]] | mark = Blue_pog.svg | area = | length = {{convert|125|mi|km|abbr=on|sigfig=1|order=flip}} | width = {{convert|25|mi|km|abbr=on|order=flip}} | thickness = unknown | terminus = [[Ross Ice Shelf]] | status = unknown }}
The '''Beardmore Glacier''' in [[Antarctica]] is one of the largest valley [[glacier]]s in the world, being {{convert|125|mi|km|abbr=on|order=flip|sigfig=1}} long and having a width of {{convert|25|mi|km|abbr=on|order=flip}}.<ref name="EBOnline">{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/57390/Beardmore-Glacier |title=Beardmore Glacier |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=www.britannica.com |publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc. |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref> It descends about {{convert|7,200|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}<ref name="EBOnline" /> from the [[Antarctic Plateau]] to the [[Ross Ice Shelf]] and is bordered by the [[Commonwealth Range]] of the [[Queen Maud Mountains]] on the eastern side and the [[Queen Alexandra Range]] of the Central [[Transantarctic Mountains]] on the western.<ref name=gnis />
The glacier is one of the main passages through the [[Transantarctic Mountains]] to the great polar plateau beyond, and was one of the early routes to the [[South Pole]] despite its steep upward incline.
The glacier was discovered and climbed by [[Ernest Shackleton]] during his [[Nimrod Expedition]] of 1908. Although Shackleton turned back before reaching the South Pole, he established the first proven route towards the pole and, in doing so, became the first person to set foot upon the polar plateau. In 1911–1912, [[Robert Falcon Scott|Captain Scott]] and his [[Terra Nova Expedition]] team reached the South Pole by similarly climbing the Beardmore. However, they reached the pole a month after [[Roald Amundsen]] and his [[Amundsen's South Pole expedition|team]], who had chosen a route up the previously unknown [[Axel Heiberg Glacier]]. It was on the way back to the Nova expedition's base camp after they left the South Pole that [[Edgar Evans]], one of the members of Scott's chosen team to go to on the final trek to the South Pole, died around the foot of Beardmore Glacier on February 17, 1912.
Beardmore Glacier was named by Shackleton after [[Sir William Beardmore]], a [[Scotland|Scottish]] industrialist and expedition sponsor born in 1856.
In 2016 the first beetle fossils, in the form of wing-cases ([[elytra]]) of [[Ball's Antarctic tundra beetle]], 14 to 20 million years old, were found on the glacier.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rare Antarctic beetle find delights|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-38145258|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 November 2016|date=29 November 2016}}</ref>
