The '''Centro Nacional de Aceleradores''' (CNA) is the centre for [[particle accelerator]]s in Spain and is based in [[Seville]]. It was created in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cienciatk.csic.es/Fotografias/CENTRO+NACIONAL+DE+ACELERADORES+:+INTERIOR+DE+UNA+NAVE_24977.html|title=CENTRO NACIONAL DE ACELERADORES : INTERIOR DE UNA NAVE|website=www.cienciatk.csic.es|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>
It combines the efforts of the [[University of Seville]], the [[Regional Government of Andalusia]] and the Spanish Higher Council for Scientific Research. It is located in the [[Cartuja 93]] Science and Technology Park.
It has three different types of [[ion accelerator]]s (3MV [[Van de Graaff generator|Van de Graaf Tandem]], [[Cyclotron]] which provides 18 [[Electronvolt|MeV]] protons and 9 MeV deuters and a 1 MV Cockcroft-Walton [[Tandem mass spectrometry|Tandem as a mass spectrometer]]) for studies in various fields. In addition, they feature a [[Positron emission tomography|PET/CT scanner]] for people, new [[Carbon-14 dating|Carbon 14]] dating systems (the MiCaDaS) and a [[Cobalt-60|60CO.2]] irradiator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://centro.us.es/cna/index.php/es/|title=Inicio|last=User|first=Super|website=centro.us.es|language=es-es|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>
