{{Infobox scientist |name = Gustav Budde-Lund |image = Gustav Budde-Lund.png |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = 11 January 1846 |birth_place = |death_date = {{d-da|19 September 1911|11 January 1846}} |death_place = |residence = |citizenship = |nationality = Danish |ethnicity = |field = [[Carcinology]], [[Entomology]] |work_institutions = |alma_mater = |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |prizes = |religion = |footnotes = |signature = }} '''Gustav Henrik Andreas Budde-Lund''' (11 January 1846 – 19 September 1911)<ref>{{cite book|author=Anden Udgave |chapter=Budde-Lund, Gustav Henrik Andreas|title=[[Salmonsens Konversationsleksikon]]|volume=26| year=1930|page=174|chapter-url=http://runeberg.org/salmonsen/2/26/0192.html|language=Danish}}</ref> was a Danish [[invertebrate zoologist]]. In 1868, he co-founded the ''[[Entomologisk Forening]]'', alongside [[Rasmus William Traugott Schlick]], [[Carl August Møller]], [[Andreas Haas (zoologist)|Andreas Haas]] and [[Ivar Frederik Christian Ammitzbøll]].{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} He was a student of entomologist [[J. C. Schiødte]], and became a leading authority on terrestrial isopods ([[Woodlouse|woodlice]], pill bugs and relatives), describing over 70 genera and around 500 species.<ref name="Wolff1993">{{cite book|first=Torben|last=Wolff|chapter=More than 200 years of crustacean research in Denmark|title=History of Carcinology|editor-first=Frank|editor-last= Truesdale|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oMQTwzwQXakC&pg=PA212|year= 1993|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-90-5410-137-6|pages=212–213}}</ref> He married in 1875 and in 1885 produced his seminal work ''Crustacea Isopoda terrestria''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.litteraturpriser.dk/1850/bgbuddelund.htm |title=G. Budde-Lund (1846-1911) |work=Danske Litteraturpriser |author=Niels Jensen |accessdate=February 21, 2009}}</ref> The woodlouse genus ''[[Buddelundiella]]'' was named in Budde-Lund's honour by [[Filippo Silvestri]] in 1897.
